                <opener>
                    <dateline>December 17, 1935</dateline>
                
                    <salute>My dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute> 
                </opener>
                <p>Thank you very much for your letter of December 14 with regard to Mr. Ford Jack's manuscript. I should like very much to see it. Won't you express to him the very real interest of this company in his work and ask him to be sure to give us the privilege of reading it as soon as it can be read? I would write him directly, except that I do not have his address. I shall be grateful for your kind offices as I have been many times in the past.</p>
                
                <p>I'll get together a collection of the clippings and advertising publicity which appeared on <hi rend="caps">THE SONG OF THE MESSIAH</hi> and will send these to you. I am sure you will be pleased with them all. Many of the reviews have been excellent.</p>
                
                <p>I am interested in your letter, too, about <hi rend="caps">BLACK ELK SPEAKS</hi>. Do you have a spare copy of the book that you could send to us so that we might consider what might be done about it? I think that I read <hi rend="caps">BLACK ELK SPEAKS</hi> myself some little time ago, but I would like to referesh my memory, and to have some of the others read it too.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely yours,</salute>
                    <signed>H.S. Latham</signed>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Branson</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Missouri</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <note>HSL:PB</note>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
